Intro: 

1. General 
- while we speak, our voices transport a variety of information 
- information can be linguistic (speech content), extralinguistic (such as identiy, speaker sex or speaker age) and paralinguistic (cues that accompany what we are saying, such as our prosody)
- very important paralinguistic cue is: emotion
- emotions play a key role in everyday interaction
- key feature: they change in real time in the context of a conversation (unlixe extralinguistic cues)
- timely and adequate reaction within a conversation, monitoring and efficient processing
- what makes our processing so efficient: flexibility

- our emotion perception is not static, but it tunes into contexts and speakers
- for example, it has been shown that listeners rely on different acoustic cues to infer emotions, depending which are more informative at the moment
- further, although speaker express emotion in very different ways, listeners are equally efficient in recognizing emotions



- aim of this paper is to understand the flexibility of emotional perception in more dephts by studying its interplay with linguistic and extralinguistic cues, by employing the phenomenon of perceptual adaptation. 
- the system also recalibrates to the current auditory context.... 

- Adaptation is powerful paradigm showing that our perceptual system constantly recalibrates is perceptual adaptation.
- in what follows, first an overview over adaptation effects in multimodal contexts
- afterwards specific to emotional adaptation



2. Perceptual Adaptation - a universal phenomenon in visual and auditory perception

- when this flexibility breaks down -> problematic
- ToDo: Jiang et al. 2022 -> linked to depression

- go through all the evidence for adaptation paradigms
- end with simultaneous opposite aftereffects (Bestelmeyer)
- but never shown for the voice domain (one aim of the present study)
- in what follows, summarise evidence for emotion perception in voices

3. Adaptation to emotions

- basic effect
- not affected by caricatures
- parameter-specific etc. 
- but potentially by other voice features: e.g. gender
